The Goal of Integration Testing

Up until now, we've been working on a smaller scale. Interacting with components manually in Storybook and programmatic unit testing with Jest & Cypress Component Testing are both very useful techniques for accessibility.

User flows like purchasing items, paying bills, or submitting forms are present in every application. But users don't interact with our applications at the component level. When your app is inaccessible, it loses users' confidence and can even lead to lawsuits as WCAG conformance applies to whole user flows.

This is where integration testing with Cypress comes in.

Integration Testing with Cypress

As mentioned earlier, there are a lot of similarities between the Component Testing and integration testing versions of Cypress.

Both run a real browser instance and feature a UI showing information about our tests.

In terms of features, the “regular” Cypress version is concerned with bigger picture page-level testing, including navigation. Cypress is also framework agnostic, meaning it doesn't care what framework (if any) is used to build your application. Depending on how well your tests are written, they could still work even if you rebuilt your site.

Installing & Configuring Cypress

Since we’ve already installed & configured Cypress for Component Testing, a lot of our setup work is done.

Inside of package.json are the scripts that run Cypress:

  • cypress:open will run Cypress with the web-based UI we can interact with.
  • cypress:run will run the test suite without a UI. We’ll use this option for Continuous Integration later.

A test script, test:e2e, also start a development server from the command line before opening Cypress.

For more info on installing Cypress in your own projects, head over to their docs.

Reading & Running a Cypress Test

Cypress integration tests look similar to the components we tested in the last section.

Open HomePage.test.js from inside of the exercise 3 directory.

For integration tests we tell Cypress to open a URL before each test, instead of mounting a component like we saw in the Component Testing lessons.

There is currently one generic test in this file that checks to see if the element with an id of “Header” contains the string “CampSpots”:

describe('HomePage', () => {
    beforeEach(() => {
        cy.visit('http://0.0.0.0:1234/')
    })

    it('should have a Header', () => {
        cy.get('#header').contains('CampSpots')
    })
})
describe('HomePage', () => {
    beforeEach(() => {
        cy.visit('http://0.0.0.0:1234/')
    })

    it('should have a Header', () => {
        cy.get('#header').contains('CampSpots')
    })
})

Run the test suite with the yarn test:e2e command in the terminal and the Cypress UI will open. The UI features a sidebar that includes information about the tests it runs.

In this scenario, the UI shows us that our Header test has passed.
